{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}} {{Infobox cemetery | name = Al Adl cemetery | image = | imagesize = | caption = | map_type = | map_size = | map_caption = | established = {{start date and age|1926}} | country = [[Saudi Arabia]] | location = Majid street, [[Mecca]] | coordinates = | latitude = | longitude = | type = | style = | owner = State | size = 50,000 square meters | graves = | interments = | website = | findagrave = | political = }}
The '''al-Adl cemetery''' ({{lang-ar|مقبرة العدل|Maqbarat al-‘Adl|lit=Cemetery of Divine Justice}}) is one of the earliest and largest resting places in Mecca. It is also the second largest cemetery in the city.
==History and location== The graveyard was opened in 1926 and its size is around 50,000 square meters.<ref name=sg18612>{{cite news|title=Al Adl: One of Makkah’s oldest cemeteries |url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentid=20120618127307 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |newspaper=Saudi Gazette |date=18 June 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728183846/http://saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentid=20120618127307 |archivedate=28 July 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> The cemetery is on Majed Street in [[Mecca]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands Attend Majed’s Funeral|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/230709|accessdate=10 August 2012|newspaper=Arab News|date=14 April 2003}}</ref> It is near [[Masjid al-Haram|Masjid Al Haram]] that is located at northeast.<ref>{{cite news|title=Salman likely new Saudi heir as Nayef dies|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2012/06/18/2003535639|accessdate=23 February 2013|newspaper=Taipei Times|date=18 June 2012|agency=AFP|location=Mecca}}</ref> The cemetery is also near Makkah governorate headquarters that is at east side.<ref name=sg18612/>
==Burials== Many eminent Saudi royals were interred in the Al Adl cemetery,<ref>{{cite news|title=King Abdullah in Makkah as Saudi Arabia prepares to bury Crown Prince Nayef|url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/region/king-abdullah-in-makkah-as-saudi-arabia-prepares-to-bury-crown-prince-nayef-2012-06-17-1.463307|accessdate=5 October 2012|work=Emirates 24/7|date=17 June 2012}}</ref> including [[Nayef bin Abdul-Aziz Al Saud|Prince Nayef]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Saudi crown prince laid to rest in Mecca|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2012/06/2012617155527692102.html|accessdate=15 August 2012|work=Al Jazeera|date=18 June 2012}}</ref> [[Mansour bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Mansour]],<ref name=sg18612/> [[Mishari bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Mishari]], [[Majid bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Majid]], [[Fawwaz bin Abdul-Aziz Al Saud|Prince Fawwaz]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Saudi royal court mourns Prince Fawaz bin Abdulaziz |url=http://www.ainalyaqeen.com/arch_2008/29_july/en3.php |accessdate=4 May 2012 |work=Ain al Yaqeen |date=29 July 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927114259/http://www.ainalyaqeen.com/arch_2008/29_july/en3.php |archivedate=27 September 2013 }}</ref> [[Sattam bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Sattam]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Sattam remembered for 45 years of service to nation |url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentid=20130213152976 |accessdate=13 February 2013 |newspaper=Saudi Gazette |date=13 February 2013 |author=Abdurahman Al Shamrani |author2=Khaled Al Faris |location=Riyadh |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006155033/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentid=20130213152976 |archivedate=6 October 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> and [[Abdullah al Faisal|Prince Abdullah Al Faisal Al Saud]].<ref name=sg18612/> [[Fahad bin Saud bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Fahd bin Saud]] also buried in the cemetery. [[Abd al-Aziz ibn Abd Allah ibn Baaz]], Prince [[Saud bin Faisal bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Saud bin Faisal Al Saud]] and Muhammad bin Saleh Al Othaimeen were also buried in the graveyard. Additionally, the cemetery has been used as a resting place for former imams of Masjid Al Haram.<ref name=sg18612/>
